You already know I am against the concept of "children's books", but the three that are exceptions would be "Emil of Lonneberga" by Lindgren (peasant boy antics in old rural Sweden), "The Flying Classroom" by Kastner (brutal Germanic school life and Mannerbund), and Lagerlof's...

... "The Wonderful Adventure of Nils" (magical travel above Sweden together w/ a wedge of wild geese). All of these are not well known, but legitimately left an impression on me. If you have (or will) kids, any of them would make a wonderful gift for Christmas, winter break, etc.
